What is Form 8843 - Statement of Exemption?

Days of presence in the United States are counted towards the Substantial Presence Test. (183 day Test).
See Substantial Presence Test Calculator. If a person , meets the Substantial Presence Test, they are considered Residents and need to file Form 1040.

But Students in F1, J1, Q Visas are exempt from Substantial Presence Test for upto 5 years, and J1 Teachers, Researchers and Physicians are exempt for 2 years. They need to inform this exemption to the IRS by filing Form 8843. The exemption helps F1, J1 students, teachers remain non resident
and file Form 1040NR-EZ.

Form 8840 - Exemption based on Closer Connection

If you are a Resident, based on Substantial Presence Test or Greencard Test, you can still ask IRS to treat you as a Non Resident, by showing your Closer connection to your Foreign Country, compared to the United States by filing Form 8840.

Form 8833 - Dual Residents who claim Tax Treaty Benefits

If you are a Resident of both United States and a Foreign Country , you can claim Tax Treaty benefits
by filing Form 8833.

